ete\n*[[Sofia Landon Geier]] (born 1949), Canadian actress and writer\n*[[Timothy Landon]] (1942\u20132007), British soldier and politician\n*[[Tina Landon]] (born 1963), American choreographer\n*[[Truman H. Landon]] (1905\u20131986), American air force general\n\n==Fictional characters==\n*[[Landon (Planet of the Apes)]]\n*[[Herbert Landon]], on the 1994\u20131998 television series ''Spider-Man''\n*[[Jodie Landon]], on the television series ''Daria''\n*Landon Carter, in the 1999 novel ''[[A Walk to Remember (novel)|A Walk to Remember]]'' by [[Nicholas Sparks]], and its [[A Walk to Remember|2002 film adaptation]]\n*The title character of the 2007 supernatural thriller film ''[[Sarah Landon and the Paranormal Hour]]''\n*Landon Kirby, a regular character on the television series ''[[Legacies (TV series)|Legacies]]'' (2018\u2013present) who is a phoenix\n\n==See also==\n*[[Landon Arena]]\n*[[Landon School]]\n*''[[Dettmer v. Landon]]'' (1986)\n*[[Harold Morton Landon Translation Award]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{given name|type=both}}\n", "name_user": "WhyamIalive12", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(Umm it me)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Landon"}
{"title_page": "Andrew Hood", "text_new": "'''Andrew Hood''' is a Canadian author. He has written two books of [[short stories]], ''Pardon Our Monsters'' (V\u00e9hicule Press) and ''The Cloaca'' (Invisible Publishing).<ref>{{cite web|title=About|url=http://www.andrewnathanhood.com/about/|accessdate=25 May 2016}}</ref> His most recent book, ''Jim Guthrie: Who Needs What'', is a work of nonfiction published as part of Invisible Publishing's Bibliophonic Series.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bibliophonic|url=http://invisiblepublishing.com/product-category/bibliophonic/|website=Invisible Publishing|accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nHood's works have won him multiple accolades, including the [[Danuta Gleed Literary Award]] for ''Pardon Our Monsters''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Montreal's Andrew Hood wins Danuta Gleed Award|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/montreals-andrew-hood-wins-danuta-gleed-award/article17986509/|website=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=25 May 2016}}</ref> His writings has appeared in ''[[Maisonneuve (magazine)|\nMaisonneuve'']], ''[[PRISM International]]'', ''[[The New Quarterly]]'', and in ''[[Joyland: A hub for short fiction|Joyland magazine]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hood|first1=Andrew|title=The Shrew's Dilemma|url=https://maisonneuve.org/contributor/338/|website=Maisonneuve|accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=PRISM contributor Andrew Hood in 2012 Journey Prize anthology|url=http://prismmagazine.ca/2012/05/03/prism-contributor-andre-hood/|website=PRISM International|accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=TNQ's summer issue is at the printers|url=http://tnq.ca/blog/tnqs-summer-issue-printers|website=The New Quarterly|accessdate=26 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423140139/http://tnq.ca/blog/tnqs-summer-issue-printers|archive-date=2016-04-23|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hood|first1=Andrew|title=Unburdened Things|url=http://www.joylandmagazine.com/regions/toronto/unburdened-things|website=Joyland|accessdate=26 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160609172456/http://www.joylandmagazine.com/regions/toronto/unburdened-things|archive-date=9 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHood lives in [[Guelph, Ontario]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hood|first1=Andrew|title=Jim Guthrie: Who Needs What|publisher=Invisible Publishing|location=Toronto|isbn=978-1-926743-53-0|pages=106|edition=1st}}<!--|accessdate=26 May 2016--></ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Pardon Our Monsters'' (2007)\n* ''The Cloaca'' (2012)\n* ''Jim Guthrie: Who Needs What'' (2015)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.andrewnathanhood.com Andrew Nathan Hood]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hood, Andrew}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Guelph]]\n[[Category:Canadian male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Ontario]]\n[[Category:Concordia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Canada-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Andrew Hood''' is a Canadian author. He has written two books of [[short stories]], ''Pardon Our Monsters'' (V\u00e9hicule Press) and ''The Cloaca'' (Invisible Publishing).<ref>{{cite web|title=About|url=http://www.andrewnathanhood.com/about/|accessdate=25 May 2016}}</ref> His most recent book, ''Jim Guthrie: Who Needs What'', is a work of nonfiction published as part of Invisible Publishing's Bibliophonic Series.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bibliophonic|url=http://invisiblepublishing.com/product-category/bibliophonic/|website=Invisible Publishing|accessdate=26 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nHood's works have won him multiple accolades, including the [[Danuta Gleed Literary Award]] for ''Pardon Our Monsters''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Montreal's Andrew Hood wins Danuta Gleed Award|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/montreals-andrew-hood-wins-danuta-gleed-award/article17986509/|website=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=25 May 2016}}</ref> His writings has appeared in ''[[Maisonneuve (magaz