{"title_page": "All She Wants to Do Is Dance", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = All She Wants to Do Is Dance\n| cover      = Allshewantstodoisdance45.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Don Henley]]\n| album      = [[Building the Perfect Beast]]\n| B-side     = Building the Perfect Beast\n| released   = February 1985\n| format     = [[7\" single|7-inch]], [[12\" single|12-inch]]\n| recorded   = 1984\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Hard rock]], [[dance rock]]\n| length     = 4:28 (album)<br />4:23 (remix edit)\n| label      = [[Geffen Records|Geffen]]\n| writer     = [[Danny Kortchmar]]\n| producer   = [[Don Henley]], [[Danny Kortchmar]], [[Greg Ladanyi]]\n| prev_title = [[The Boys of Summer (song)|The Boys of Summer]]\n| prev_year  = 1984\n| next_title = [[Not Enough Love in the World]]\n| next_year  = 1985\n| misc       = {{Audio sample\n | type        = single\n | file        = Don Henley - All She Wants to Do Is Dance.ogg\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''All She Wants to Do Is Dance'''\" is a song written by [[Danny Kortchmar]] and performed by [[Don Henley]], co-lead vocalist and drummer for [[Eagles (band)|Eagles]]. It was released as the second single from Henley's second studio solo album, ''[[Building the Perfect Beast]]'', being Henley's sixth single. It was one of Henley's most commercially successful singles.\n\n==Background==\nThe single became a ''Billboard'' Top 10 hit in March 1985, peaking at number 9, and also became his third song to top the [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks|Top Rock Tracks]] chart.<ref>[[Joel Whitburn|Whitburn, Joel]] (2004). ''The Billboard Book of Top 40 Hits'', 8th Edition (Billboard Publications), page 282.</ref> Background singing for the song was provided by [[Patty Smyth]] of the group [[Scandal (American band)|Scandal]], and Martha Davis, lead singer of The Motels.<ref>[[allmusic.com]] (2016). \"Song Review by Stewart Mason\" allmusic.com</ref>\n\n==Composition==\nWhen Kortchmar was asked about the song he said \"I had the groove and the music going. That record was made back when the technology had just started to really take over in music. I had one of the first [[Yamaha DX7]]s, which was a keyboard that was used a ton in the '80s, but we ended up luckily getting one of the first ones in the United States. It's a synthesizer keyboard, and I used it to get that sound that you hear the record starting with.\"<ref>http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=21864</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe commercial U.S. 7\" vinyl version has a slightly different intro than the LP version from ''Building the Perfect Beast''.\n\n==Critical reception==\n[[John Leland (journalist)|John Leland]] from ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' magazine wrote about the [[12-inch single]] version of the song saying \"...this mother whomps from the git with punchy electronic drums and a mix that keeps one foot off the ground for a full seven-and-a-half minutes. Henley's post-hedonist vision of apocalypse is twisted.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Don Henley \"All She Wants To Do Is Dance\" (Geffen)|author=John Leland|authorlink=John Leland (journalist)|publisher=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|date=July 1985|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ImJFcBcCvUoC&pg=PA34&dq=spin+magazine+1985+all+she+wants+to+do+is+dance&hl=en&ei=q8hxTLW8F4u6sAP7hcyLCw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false|pages=34|accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Don Henley]] \u2013 lead vocals, drums, harmony vocals\n* [[Danny Kortchmar]] \u2013 guitar\n* [[David Paich]] \u2013 synthesizer\n* [[Steve Porcaro]] \u2013 programming\n* [[The Motels|Martha Davis]] \u2013 harmony vocals\n* [[Patty Smyth]] \u2013 harmony vocals\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Chart performance==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Chart (1985)\n! Peak<br>position\n|-\n| Canadian ''RPM'' Top Singles<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-110.01-e.php?PHPSESSID=n960fqdttrg067djojbm2isq61&q