m rock hits (United States)#1985|List of number-one mainstream rock hits (United States)]]\n*[[Ronald Reagan in music]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|don-henley|all-she-wants-to-do-is-dance}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* [http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x1ub8i_don-henley-all-she-wants-to-do-is-d_music Music Video]\n\n{{Don Henley}}\n\n[[Category:1985 singles]]\n[[Category:Don Henley songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Danny Kortchmar]]\n[[Category:1984 songs]]\n[[Category:Geffen Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs about dancing]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Danny Kortchmar]]\n[[Category:Ronald Reagan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = All She Wants to Do Is Dance\n| cover      = Allshewantstodoisdance45.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Don Henley]]\n| album      = [[Building the Perfect Beast]]\n| B-side     = Building the Perfect Beast\n| released   = February 1985\n| format     = [[7\" single|7-inch]], [[12\" single|12-inch]]\n| recorded   = 1984\n| studio     =\n| genre      = \n| length     = 4:28 (album)<br />4:23 (remix edit)\n| label      = [[Geffen Records|Geffen]]\n| writer     = [[Danny Kortchmar]]\n| producer   = [[Don Henley]], [[Danny Kortchmar]], [[Greg Ladanyi]]\n| prev_title = [[The Boys of Summer (song)|The Boys of Summer]]\n| prev_year  = 1984\n| next_title = [[Not Enough Love in the World]]\n| next_year  = 1985\n| misc       = {{Audio sample\n | type        = single\n | file        = Don Henley - All She Wants to Do Is Dance.ogg\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''All She Wants to Do Is Dance'''\" is a song written by [[Danny Kortchmar]] and performed by [[Don Henley]], co-lead vocalist and drummer for [[Eagles (band)|Eagles]]. It was released as the second single from Henley's second studio solo album, ''[[Building the Perfect Beast]]'', being Henley's sixth single. It was one of Henley's most commercially successful singles.\n\n==Background==\nThe single became a ''Billboard'' Top 10 hit in March 1985, peaking at number 9, and also became his third song to top the [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks|Top Rock Tracks]] chart.<ref>[[Joel Whitburn|Whitburn, Joel]] (2004). ''The Billboard Book of Top 40 Hits'', 8th Edition (Billboard Publications), page 282.</ref> Background singing for the song was provided by [[Patty Smyth]] of the group [[Scandal (American band)|Scandal]], and Martha Davis, lead singer of The Motels.<ref>[[allmusic.com]] (2016). \"Song Review by Stewart Mason\" allmusic.com</ref>\n\n==Composition==\nWhen Kortchmar was asked about the song he said \"I had the groove and the music going. That record was made back when the technology had just started to really take over in music. I had one of the first [[Yamaha DX7]]s, which was a keyboard that was used a ton in the '80s, but we ended up luckily getting one of the first ones in the United States. It's a synthesizer keyboard, and I used it to get that sound that you hear the record starting with.\"<ref>http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=21864</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe commercial U.S. 7\" vinyl version has a slightly different intro than the LP version from ''Building the Perfect Beast''.\n\n==Critical reception==\n[[John Leland (journalist)|John Leland]] from ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' magazine wrote about the [[12-inch single]] version of the song saying \"...this mother whomps from the git with punchy electronic drums and a mix that keeps one foot off the ground for a full seven-and-a-half minutes. Henley's post-hedonist vision of apocalypse is twisted.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Don Henley \"All She Wants To Do Is Dance\" (Geffen)|author=John Leland|authorlink=John Leland (journalist)|publisher=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|date=July 1985|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ImJFcBcCvUoC&pg=PA34&dq=spin+magazine+1985+all+she+wants+to+do+is+dance&hl=en&ei=q8hxTLW8F4u6sAP7hcyLCw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false|pages=34|accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Don Henley]] \u2013 lead vocals, drums, harmony vocals\n* [[Danny Kortchmar]] \u2013 guitar\n* [[David Paich]] \u2013 synthesizer\n* [[Steve Porcaro]] \u2013 programming\n* [[The Motels|Martha Davis]] \u2013 harmony vocals\n* [[Patty Smyth]] \u2013 harmony vocals\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Chart performance==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Chart (1985)\n! Peak<br>position\n|-\n| Canadian ''RPM'' Top Singles<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-110.01-e.php?PHPSESSID=n960fqdttrg067djojbm2isq61&q1=Don+Henley&q2=Top+Singles&interval=20|title=Results \u2013 RPM \u2013 Library and Archives Canada \u2013 Top Singles|work=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|accessdate=April 1, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022074711/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-110.01-e.php?PHPSESSID=n960fqdttrg067djojbm2isq61&q1=Don+Henley&q2=Top+Singles&interval=20|archive-date=October 22, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| 13\n|-\n| U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=don henley|chart=Hot 100}}|title=Don Henley Album & Song Chart History \u2013 Hot 100|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=April 1, 2011}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| 9\n|-\n| U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot Dance Club Play<ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=don henley|chart=Dance/Club Play Songs}}|title=Don Henley Album & Song Chart History \u2013 Dance/Club Play Songs|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=April 1, 2011}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| 10\n|-\n| U.S. ''Billboard'' Top Rock Tracks<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p4474/charts-awards/billboard-singles|pure_url=yes}}|title=allmusic ((( Don Henley > Charts & Awards > Billboard Singles )))|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=April 1, 2011}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| 1\n|-\n| U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot R&B Singles<ref>https://www.billboard.com/music/don-henley/chart-history/r-b-hip-hop-songs/song/333674</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| 65\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year-end chart (1985) !! Rank\n|-\n|[[Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 1985|US Top Pop Singles (''Billboard'')]]<ref>{{cite magazine|date=December 28, 1985 |title=1985 The Year in Music & Video: Top Pop Singles |page=T-21 |journal=Billboard |volume=97 |issue=52 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|97\n|}\n\n==Other versions==\nThe single \"All She Wanna Do is Dance\" by [[David Guetta]] and [[Niles Mason]] uses samples of this song.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of number-one mainstream rock hits (United States)#1985|List of number-one mainstream rock hits (United States)]]\n*[[Ronald Reagan in music]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|don-henley|all-she-wants-to-do-is-dance}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* [http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x1ub8i_don-henley-all-she-wants-to-do-is-d_music Music Video]\n\n{{Don Henley}}\n\n[[Category:1985 singles]]\n[[Category:Don Henley songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Danny Kortchmar]]\n[[Category:1984 songs]]\n[[Category:Geffen Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs about dancing]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Danny Kortchmar]]\n[[Category:Ronald Reagan]]\n", "name_user": "74.97.187.36", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/All_She_Wants_to_Do_Is_Dance"}
{"title_page": "Petals for Armor II", "text_new": "{{linkrot|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Petals for Armor II\n| type         = EP\n| artist       = [[Hayley Williams]]\n| cover        = Hayley Williams - Petals for Armor II.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = April 2020<ref name=\"iheart\">{{Cite web|url=https://alt961.iheart.com/content/2020-03-18-hayley-williams-updates-fans-on-petals-for-armor-ii-release/|title=Hayley Williams Updates Fans On 'Petals For Armor II' Release|website=Alt 96.1|accessdate=Apr 13, 2020}}</ref>\n| recorded     = 2019\u201320\n| studio       = {{flatlist|\n* East Iris Studios\n* Music Friends\n}}\n| genre        = \n| length       = \n| label        = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| producer     = {{flatlist|\n* [[Taylor York]]\n* Hayley Williams\n* Daniel James\n}}\n| prev_title   = [[Petals for Armor I]]\n| prev_year    = 2020\n| next_title   = [[Petals for Armor]]\n| next_year    = 2020\n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = Petals for Armor II\n | type        = EP\n | single1     = Roses/Lotus/Violet/Iris\n | single1date = March 19, 2020\n | single2     = Over Yet\n | single2date = April 2, 2020\n | single3     = My Friend\n | single3date = April 9, 2020\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Petals for Armor II''''' is the second [[extended play]] (EP) by American singer-songwriter and [[Paramore]] frontwoman [[Hayley Williams]]. It is scheduled to be released on [[Atlantic Records]] in April 2020,<ref name=\"iheart\" /> as the second in a series of releases in the ''[[Petals for Armor]]'' era.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gTuq6_bqUEk|title=Hayley Williams - Hayley Williams and Zane Lowe \"Petals for Armor I\" Apple Music Interview|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref> Williams explained the inspiration behind its title is due to her belief that \"the best way for me to protect myself is to be vulnerable.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/hayley-williams-explains-meaning-of-petals-for-armor-2600097|title=Hayley Williams explains meaning of Petals For Armor: \"The way for me to protect myself best is to be vulnerable\"|work=[[NME]]|date=January 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''Petals for Armor II'' was produced by American musician, songwriter, and record producer [[Taylor York]] and was written throughout 2019 during Paramore's hiatus after touring in support of their fifth studio album, ''[[After Laughter]]'' (2017). The lead single, \"Roses/Lotus/Violet/Iris\", was released on March 19, 2020.\n\n==Background==\nFollowing extensive touring in support of [[Paramore]]'s fifth studio album ''[[After Laughter]]'' (2017), [[Hayley Williams]] expressed her feelings about the group's future moving forward explaining that they were not breaking up, however needed time away from writing and touring.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.altpress.com/news/hayley-williams-paramore-future/|title=Hayley Williams addresses Paramore's future in emotional interview|work=Alternative Press|date=March 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.altpress.com/news/hayley-williams-petals-for-armor-simmer/|title=Paramore had to \"get quiet for a minute\" for Hayley Williams' exploration|first=Koltan|last=Greenwood|date=January 23, 2020}}</ref> In an interview with [[BBC Radio]], in January 2020, Williams explained her process behind developing ''[[Petals for Armor]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8548702/hayley-williams-simmer-video-solo-paramore|title=Hayley Williams' First Solo Single Is Here: Watch the Paramore Frontwoman's Horror Flick 'Simmer' Video|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|\"I'm so ready and so incredibly humbled to get to share this project... Making it was a scary, empowering experience. Some of my proudest moments as a lyricist happened while writing 'PETALS FOR ARMOR.' And I was able to get my hands a little dirtier than usual when it came to instrumentation. I'm in a band with my favorite musicians so I never really feel the need to step into a role as a player when it comes to Paramore records. This project, however, benefited from a little bit of musical na\u00efvet\u00e9 and rawness and so I experimented quite a bit more. I made this with some of the closest people to me. Their respective talents really shine bright throughout the record. I like to think we all make each other better and the result is something that sounds and FEELS exactly as I'd hoped it would. Now that it's time to put it all out there, I can finally exhale. I'm excited to let people in to experience a different side of myself that I've only very recently become familiar with.\"}}\n\n==Singles==\n\"Roses/Lotus/Violet/Iris\" was released to [[Music download|digital download]] and [[streaming media|streaming]] platforms as the lead single on March 19, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/roses-lotus-violet-iris-single/1503157571|title=\u200eRoses / Lotus / Violet / Iris - Single by Hayley Williams|accessdate=Apr 13, 2020|via=music.apple.com}}</ref>\n\n==Confirmed tracks==\n* \"Roses/Lotus/Violet/Iris\" <small>(Hayley Williams, Taylor York, and Daniel James)</small>\n* \"Over Yet\"\n* \"My Friend\"\n\n==Credits and personnel==\nCredits adapted from this [[YouTube]] description.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bRA6xocqmow</ref>\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''Musicians'''\n* [[Hayley Williams]] \u2013 primary artist, lead vocals, keyboards, guitar\n* [[Taylor York]] \u2013 production, additional instrumentation\n* Joey Howard \u2013 bass guitar, keyboards\n* Aaron Steele \u2013 drums, percussion, congas\n* Benjamin Kaufman \u2013 violin, chin cello\n{{col-2}}\n'''Additional personnel'''\n* Daniel James \u2013 string arrangements, additional production\n* Julien Baker \u2013 background vocals\n* Phoebe Bridgers \u2013 background vocals\n* Lucy Dacus \u2013 background vocals\n* [[Carlos de la Garza (music producer)|Carlos de la Garza]] \u2013 mixing engineer\n* [[Dave Cooley]] \u2013 mastering engineer\n* Kevin \"K-Bo\" Boettger \u2013 assistant engineer\n* Michael Craver \u2013 assistant engineer, assistant mixing engineer\n* David Fitzgibbons \u2013 assistant engineer, assistant mixing engineer\n* Michelle Freetly \u2013 assistant engineer\n* Jake Butler \u2013 assistant engineer\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Hayley Williams}}\n\n[[Category:2020 EPs]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records EPs]]\n[[Category:Hayley Williams albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{linkrot|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Petals for Armor II\n| type         = EP\n| artist       = [[Hayley Williams]]\n| cover        = Hayley Williams - Petals for Armor II.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = April 2020<ref name=\"iheart\">https://alt961.iheart.com/content/2020-03-18-hayley-williams-updates-fans-on-petals-for-armor-ii-release/</ref>\n| recorded     = 2019\u201320\n| studio       = {{flatlist|\n* East Iris Studios\n* Music Friends\n}}\n| genre        = \n| length       = \n| label        = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| producer     = {{flatlist|\n* [[Taylor York]]\n* Hayley Williams\n* Daniel James\n}}\n| prev_title   = [[Petals for Armor I]]\n| prev_year    = 2020\n| next_title   = [[Petals for Armor]]\n| next_year    = 2020\n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = Petals for Armor II\n | type        = EP\n | single1     = Roses/Lotus/Violet/Iris\n | single1date = March 19, 2020\n | single2     = Over Yet\n | single2date = April 2, 2020\n | single3     = My Friend\n | single3date = April 9, 2020\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Petals for Armor II''''' is the second [[extended play]] (EP) by American singer-songwriter and [[Paramore]] frontwoman [[Hayley Williams]]. It is scheduled to be released on [[Atlantic Records]] in April 2020,<ref name=\"iheart\" /> as the second in a series of releases in the ''[[Petals for Armor]]'' era.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gTuq6_bqUEk|title=Hayley Williams - Hayley Williams and Zane Lowe \"Petals for Armor I\" Apple Music Interview|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref> Williams explained the inspiration behind its title is due to her belief that \"the best way for me to protect myself is to be vulnerable.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/hayley-williams-explains-meaning-of-petals-for-armor-2600097|title=Hayley Williams explains meaning of Petals For Armor: \"The way for me to protect myself best is to be vulnerable\"|work=[[NME]]|date=January 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''Petals for Armor II'' was produced by American musician, songwriter, and record producer [[Taylor York]] and was written throughout 2019 during Paramore's hiatus after touring in support of their fifth studio album, ''[[After Laughter]]'' (2017). The lead single, \"Roses/Lotus/Violet/Iris\", was released on March 19, 2020.\n\n==Background==\nFollowing extensive touring in support of [[Paramore]]'s fifth studio album ''[[After Laughter]]'' (2017), [[Hayley Williams]] expressed her feelings about the group's future moving forward explaining that they were not breaking up, however needed time away from writing and touring.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.altpress.com/news/hayley-williams-paramore-future/|title=Hayley Williams addresses Paramore's future in emotional interview|work=Alternative Press|date=March 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.altpress.com/news/hayley-williams-petals-for-armor-simmer/|title=Paramore had to \"get quiet for a minute\" for Hayley Williams' exploration|first=Koltan|last=Greenwood|date=January 23, 2020}}</ref> In an interview with [[BBC Radio]], in January 2020, Williams explained her process behind developing ''[[Petals for Armor]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8548702/hayley-williams-simmer-video-solo-paramore|title=Hayley Williams' First Solo Single Is Here: Watch the Paramore Frontwoman's Horror Flick 'Simmer' Video|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|\"I'm so ready and so incredibly humbled to get to share this project... Making it was a scary, empowering experience. Some of my proudest moments as a lyricist happened while writing 'PETALS FOR ARMOR.' And I was able to get my hands a little dirtier than usual when it came to instrumentation. I'm in a band with my favorite musicians so I never really feel the need to step into a role as a player when it comes to Paramore records. This project, however, benefited from a little bit of musical na\u00efvet\u00e9 and rawness and so I experimented quite a bit more. I made this with some of the closest people to me. Their respective talents really shine bright throughout the record. I like to think we all make each other better and the result is something that sounds and FEELS exactly as I'd hoped it would. Now that it's time to put it all out there, I can finally exhale. I'm excited to let people in to experience a different side of myself that I've only very recently become familiar with.\"}}\n\n==Singles==\n\"Roses/Lotus/Violet/Iris\" was released to [[Music download|digital download]] and [[streaming media|streaming]] platforms as the lead single on March 19, 2020.<ref>https://music.apple.com/us/album/roses-lotus-violet-iris-single/1503157571</ref>\n\n==Confirmed tracks==\n* \"Roses/Lotus/Violet/Iris\" <small>(Hayley Williams, Taylor York, and Daniel James)</small>\n* \"Over Yet\"\n* \"My Friend\"\n\n==Credits and personnel==\nCredits adapted from this [[YouTube]] description.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bRA6xocqmow</ref>\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''Musicians'''\n* [[Hayley Williams]] \u2013 primary artist, lead vocals, keyboards, guitar\n* [[Taylor York]] \u2013 production, additional instrumentation\n* Joey Howard \u2013 bass guitar, keyboards\n* Aaron Steele \u2013 drums, percussion, congas\n* Benjamin Kaufman \u2013 violin, chin cello\n{{col-2}}\n'''Additional personnel'''\n* Daniel James \u2013 string arrangements, additional production\n* Julien Baker \u2013 background vocals\n* Phoebe Bridgers \u2013 background vocals\n* Lucy Dacus \u2013 background vocals\n* [[Carlos de la Garza (music producer)|Carlos de la Garza]] \u2013 mixing engineer\n* [[Dave Cooley]] \u2013 mastering engineer\n* Kevin \"K-Bo\" Boettger \u2013 assistant engineer\n* Michael Craver \u2013 assistant engineer, assistant mixing engineer\n* David Fitzgibbons \u2013 assistant engineer, assistant mixing engineer\n* Michelle Freetly \u2013 assistant engineer\n* Jake Butler \u2013 assistant engineer\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Hayley Williams}}\n\n[[Category:2020 EPs]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records EPs]]\n[[Category:Hayley Williams albums]]\n", "name_user": "Mdaniels5757", "label": "safe", "comment": "Filled in 2 bare reference(s) with reFill 2", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petals_for_Armor_II"}
{"title_page": "Andrew Heywood", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n\n'''Andrew Heywood''' is a British author of textbooks on [[politics]] and [[political science]].<ref name=\"SwainTextbookCase\">{{cite news|last1=Swain|first1=Harriet|title=A textbook case for writing one|url=http://www.lexisnexis.com/hottopics/lnacademic/?verb=sr&csi=235861|accessdate=24 September 2017|publisher=The Times Higher Education Supplement|date=5 October 2007}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* ''Political Ideologies: An Introduction'' (1992, Palgrave MacMillan)\n* ''Political Ideas and Concepts: An Introduction''  (1994, Palgrave MacMillan)<ref name=\"Sarraga\">{{cite news|last1=Sarraga|first1=Jessica|title=Free and just states of mind -- Political Ideas and Concepts (book review)|publisher=The Times Educational Supplement; London|date=20 May 1994}}</ref>\n* ''Political Theory: An Introduction'', first appeared as ''Political Ideas and Concepts: An Introduction''  (1994, Palgrave MacMillan)<ref name=\"Sarraga\"/><ref name=\"IsmsandIsnts\">{{cite news|title=Politics: the isms and isn'ts|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/books/politics-the-isms-and-isnts/157058.article|accessdate=24 September 2017|publisher=Times Higher Education|date=18 February 2000}}</ref>\n* ''Politics'' (1997, Palgrave MacMillan)<ref name=\"ConleyThoroughness\">{{cite news|last1=Conley|first1=Frank|title=Thoroughness wins the vote (book review)|publisher=The Times Educational Supplement; London|date=3 October 1997}}</ref>\n* ''Key Concepts in Politics'' (2000, Palgrave MacMillan)\n* ''British Politics'' (2008, Palgrave MacMillan)\n* ''Essentials of UK Politics'' (2008, Palgrave MacMillan)\n* ''Global Politics'' (2011, Palgrave MacMillan)\n* ''Key Concepts in Politics and International Relations'' (2015, Palgrave)\n* ''Essentials of UK Politics: For as and A-Level'' (2017, Palgrave)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Mike Arrington]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://techcrunch.com/author/mike-butcher/ TechCrunch author page] - Mike Butcher\n* [http://andrewheywood.co.uk Andrew Heywood]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heywood, Andrew}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British male writers]]\n\n\n{{UK-journalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n\n'''Andrew Heywood''' is a British author of textbooks on [[politics]] and [[political science]].<ref name=\"SwainTextbookCase\">{{cite news|last1=Swain|first1=Harriet|title=A textbook case for writing one|url=http://www.lexisnexis.com/hottopics/lnacademic/?verb=sr&csi=235861|accessdate=24 September 2017|publisher=The Times Higher Education Supplement|date=5 October 2007}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* ''Political Ideologies: An Introduction'' (1992, Palgrave MacMillan)\n* ''Political Ideas and Concepts: An Introduction''  (1994, Palgrave MacMillan)<ref name=\"Sarraga\">{{cite news|last1=Sarraga|first1=Jessica|title=Free and just states of mind -- Political Ideas and Concepts (book review)|publisher=The Times Educational Supplement; London|date=20 May 1994}}</ref>\n* ''Political Theory: An Introduction'', first appeared as ''Political Ideas and Concepts: An Introduction''  (1994, Palgrave MacMillan)<ref name=\"Sarraga\"/><ref name=\"IsmsandIsnts\">{{cite news|title=Politics: the isms and isn'ts|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/books/politics-the-isms-and-isnts/157058.article|accessdate=24 September 2017|publisher=Times Higher Education|date=18 February 2000}}</ref>\n* ''Politics'' (1997, Palgrave MacMillan)<ref name=\"ConleyThoroughness\">{{cite news|last1=Conley|first1=Frank|title=Thoroughness wins the vote (book review)|publisher=The Times Educational Supplement; London|date=3 October 1997}}</ref>\n* ''Key Concepts in Politics'' (2000, Palgrave MacMillan)\n* ''British Politics'' (2008, Palgrave MacMillan)\n* ''Essentials of UK Politics'' (2008, Palgrave MacMillan)\n* ''Global Politics'' (2011, Palgrave MacMillan)\n* ''Key Concepts in Politics and International Relations'' (2015, Palgrave)\n* ''Essentials of UK Politics: For as and A-Level'' (2017, Palgrave)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Mike Arrington]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://techcrunch.com/author/mike-butcher/ TechCrunch author page] - Mike Butcher\n* [http://andrewheywood.co.uk Andrew Heywood]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heywood, Andrew}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British male writers]]\n\n\n{{UK-journalist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_Heywood"}
{"title_page": "Trimmer (electronics)", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=May 2008}}\n[[File:12 surface mount potentiometers.jpg|thumb|right|Trimmer potentiometers or \"trimpots\"]]\n\nA '''trimmer'''<ref>[http://www.kpsec.freeuk.com/components/vres.htm#presets Variable Resistors; The Electronics Club.]</ref> is a miniature adjustable electrical component. It is meant to be set correctly when installed in some device, and never seen or adjusted by the device's user. Trimmers can be variable resistors ([[potentiometer]]s), [[variable capacitor]]s, or trimmable [[inductor]]s. They are common in precision circuitry like [[Audiovisual|A/V]] components, and may need to be adjusted when the equipment is serviced. Trimpots are often used to initially calibrate equipment after manufacturing. Unlike many other variable controls, trimmers are mounted directly on [[circuit board]]s, turned with a small [[screwdriver]] and rated for many fewer adjustments over their lifetime. Trimmers like trimmable inductors and trimmable [[capacitor]]s are usually found in [[superhet]] [[radio]] and [[television]] receivers, in the [[intermediate frequency]] (IF), [[oscillator]] and radio frequency (RF) circuits. They are adjusted into the right position during the alignment procedure of the receiver.\n\n'''Presets''' in electronics are adjustable components to which the user of the device has no access.  They are intended to be set during manufacture or as part of maintenance and repair.  A range of different [[passive component]]s can be made as presets, including [[resistor]]s, [[capacitor]]s, and [[inductor]]s.\n\n== General considerations ==\nTrimmers come in a variety of sizes and levels of precision. For example, multi-turn trim potentiometers exist, in which it takes several turns of the adjustment screw to reach the end value. This allows for very high degrees of accuracy. Often they make use of a worm-gear (rotary track) or a leadscrew (linear track).<ref>{{cite web|title=Trimpot - Trimmer potentiometer|url=http://www.resistorguide.com/trimpot/|work=the Resistor Guide|accessdate=20 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe position on the component of the adjustment often needs to be considered for accessibility after the circuit is assembled.  Both top- and side-adjust trimmers are available to facilitate this.  The adjustment of presets is often fixed in place with sealing wax after the adjustment is made to prevent movement by vibration.  This also serves as an indication if the device has been tampered with.\n\n==Resistors==\nResistor trimmers generally come in the form of a [[potentiometer]] (pot), often called a '''trimpot'''.  Potentiometers have three terminals, but can be used as a normal two-terminal resistor by joining the wiper to one of the other terminals, or just using two terminals.  ''Trimpot'' was originally a trademark of [[Bourns, Inc.]], the trimpot having been patented by Marlan Bourns in 1952, but the term has since become [[generic trademark|generic]].\n\nTwo types of preset resistor are commonly found in circuits.  The skeleton potentiometer works like a regular circular potentiometer, but is stripped of its enclosure, shaft, and fixings.  The full movement of a skeleton potentiometer is less than a single turn.  The other type is the multi-turn potentiometer which move the slider along the resistive track via a [[worm gear]] arrangement.  The gearing is such that multiple turns of the adjustment screw are required to move the slider the full distance along the resistive track.  Some, possibly the majority, of multi-turn pots have a linear track rather than a circular one.<ref>E. Stocks, Malcom Doughton, C. Duncan, ''Basic Science and Electronics'', Thomson Learning, 1998 {{ISBN|1861527594}}</ref>\n\nmulti-turn trim potentiometers exist, in which it takes several turns of the adjustment screw to reach the end value. This allows for very high degrees of accuracy. Often they make use of a worm-gear (rotary track) or a leadscrew (linear track).<ref>{{cite web|title=Trimpot - Trimmer potentiometer|url=http://www.resistorguide.com/trimpot/|work=the Resistor Guide|accessdate=20 February 2013}}</ref> \n\n{|\n|-\n|[[File:Nedap ESD1 - Keyboard controller PCB - Bourns 3386-8588.jpg|upright=0.6|thumb|A top-adjust trimpot wtih sealing wax]]\n|[[File:Siemens RC 826 - trimmer pot-1728.jpg|upright=0.6|thumb|A side-adjust skeleton trimpot]]\n|[[File:10K trimpot.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|A trimpot with knurling to allow finger adjustment]]\n|[[File:Bourns TRIMIT trimming potentiometer 2016-11-06.jpg|upright=0.8|thumb|A linear multi-turn trimpot]]\n|[[File:\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0446\u0438\u0437\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0435\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440.jpg|upright=0.6|thumb|A top-adjust circular-track multi-turn trimpot]]\n|}\n\n==Capacitors==\nTrimming capacitors can be multi-plate [[parallel-plate capacitor]]s with a dielectric for between plates for increased capacitance.  However, at [[SHF]] only very small values of capacitance are needed.  Presets at these frequencies are commonly a glass tube with plates at either end.  The top plate is adjusted by means of a screw to which it is attached at the top of the cylinder.\n\n==Inductors==\nA common way of making preset inductors in radios is to wind the inductor on a plastic tube.  A high [[permeability]] core material is inserted into the cylinder in the form of a screw.  Winding the core further in to the inductor increases inductance and vice versa.  It is normally necessary to use non-metallic tools to adjust inductors.  A steel screwdriver will increase the inductance while it is being adjusted and it will fall again when the screwdriver is removed.\n\nAt VHF and SHF, only small values of inductance are usually needed.  Inductors can be made of open coils of a few turns.  They can be tuned by squeezing the coils together or by pulling them apart as the inductance needs to be increased or decreased respectively.\n\n==Tuned circuits==\n{{see also|Tuner (radio)}}\nAn adjustable tuned circuit can be formed in the same way as a preset inductor.  The inductor and its resonant capacitor are commonly contained in a metal can for shielding with a hole at the top to give access to the adjustable core.  Tuned transformers can also be constructed this way with two windings on the same core.  This is a common component in the [[intermediate frequency|IF stage]] of radios which have a [[double-tuned amplifier]] format.\n\n{|\n|-\n|[[File:IF transformer.JPG|thumb|upright=0.5|IF double-tuned transformer]]\n|[[File:Transformateur FI.jpg|thumb|upright|IF transformer can]]\n|[[File:IF transformer cutaway.jpg|thumb|upright=0.35|IF transformer cutaway]]\n|}\n\n==Distributed-element circuit==\n[[Distributed-element circuit]]s often use the component known as a [[Stub (electronics)|stub]].  In printed [[Planar transmission line|planar formats]] such as [[microstrip]], stubs can be trimmed by removing material with a scalpel or adding material by soldering on copper foil or even just pressing on strips of [[indium]].  This is useful for prototypes and pre-production runs, but is usually not done on production items.\n\n==Applications==\nThey are common in precision circuitry like [[Audiovisual|A/V]] components, and may need to be adjusted when the equipment is serviced. Trimpots are often used to initially calibrate equipment after manufacturing. Unlike many other variable controls, trimmers are mounted directly on [[circuit board]]s, turned with a small [[screwdriver]] and rated for many fewer adjustments over their lifetime. Trimmers like trimmable inductors and trimmable [[capacitor]]s are usually found in [[superhet]] [[radio]] and [[television]] receivers, in the [[intermediate frequency]] (IF), [[oscillator]] and radio frequency (RF) circuits. They are adjusted into the correct position during the alignment procedure.\n\n==Electronic symbols==\n[[Electronic symbol]]s for adjustable components.\n<gallery>\nFile:Potentiometer_symbol.svg|Electronic symbol for a resistive trimmer\nFile:Trimmer capacitor symbol GOST.svg|Electronic symbol for a capacitive trimmer\nFile:Reguleeritav pool.jpg|Electronic symbol for an adjustable inductor\n</gallery>\nn circuit diagrams, the symbol for a variable component is the symbol for a fixed component with a diagonal line through it terminating in an arrow head.  For a preset component, the diagonal line terminates in a \"T\" shape. \n\n==See also==\n* [[Laser trimming]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.robotroom.com/Trimpots.html Trimmer potentiometers (examples and internals)], Robot Room\n* [https://www.bourns.com/docs/technical-documents/technical-library/trimmers/technical-articles/trmrpmr.pdf Highlights from Trimmer Primers] - Bourns\n\n{{Electronic component}}\n\n[[Category:Resistive components]]\n[[Category:Capacitors]]\n\n[[de:Potentiometer#Trimmpotentiometer]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=May 2008}}\n[[File:12 surface mount potentiometers.jpg|thumb|right|Trimmer potentiometers or \"trimpots\"]]\n\nA '''trimmer'''<ref>[http://www.kpsec.freeuk.com/components/vres.htm#presets Variable Resistors; The Electronics Club.]</ref> is a miniature adjustable electrical component. It is meant to be set correctly when installed in some device, and never seen or adjusted by the device's user. Trimmers can be variable resistors ([[potentiometer]]s), [[variable capacitor]]s, or trimmable [[inductor]]s. They are common in precision circuitry like [[Audiovisual|A/V]] components, and may need to be adjusted when the equipment is serviced. Trimpots are often used to initially calibrate equipment after manufacturing. Unlike many other variable controls, trimmers are mounted directly on [[circuit board]]s, turned with a small [[screwdriver]] and rated for many fewer adjustments over their lifetime. Trimmers like trimmable inductors and trimmable [[capacitor]]s are usually found in [[superhet]] [[radio]] and [[television]] receivers, in the [[intermediate frequency]] (IF), [[oscillator]] and radio frequency (RF) circuits. They are adjusted into the right position during the alignment procedure of the receiver.\n\n'''Presets''' in electronics are adjustable components to which the user of the device has no access.  They are intended to be set during manufacture or as part of maintenance and repair.  A range of different [[passive component]]s can be made as presets, including [[resistor]]s, [[capacitor]]s, and [[inductor]]s.\n\n== General considerations ==\nTrimmers come in a variety of sizes and levels of precision. For example, multi-turn trim potentiometers exist, in which it takes several turns of the adjustment screw to reach the end value. This allows for very high degrees of accuracy. Often they make use of a worm-gear (rotary track) or a leadscrew (linear track).<ref>{{cite web|title=Trimpot - Trimmer potentiometer|url=http://www.resistorguide.com/trimpot/|work=the Resistor Guide|accessdate=20 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe position on the component of the adjustment often needs to be considered for accessibility after the circuit is assembled.  Both top- and side-adjust trimmers are available to facilitate this.  The adjustment of presets is often fixed in place with sealing wax after the adjustment is made to prevent movement by vibration.  This also serves as an indication if the device has been tampered with.\n\n==Resistors==\nResistor trimmers generally come in the form of a [[potentiometer]] (pot), often called a '''trimpot'''.  Potentiometers have three terminals, but can be used as a normal two-terminal resistor by joining the wiper to one of the other terminals, or just using two terminals.  ''Trimpot'' was originally a trademark of [[Bourns, Inc.]], the trimpot having been patented by Marlan Bourns in 1952, but the term has since become [[generic trademark|generic]].\n\nTwo types of preset resistor are commonly found in circuits.  The skeleton potentiometer works like a regular circular potentiometer, but is stripped of its enclosure, shaft, and fixings.  The full movement of a skeleton potentiometer is less than a single turn.  The other type is the multi-turn potentiometer which move the slider along the resistive track via a [[worm gear]] arrangement.  The gearing is such that multiple turns of the adjustment screw are required to move the slider the full distance along the resistive track.  Some, possibly the majority, of multi-turn pots have a linear track rather than a circular one.<ref>E. Stocks, Malcom Doughton, C. Duncan, ''Basic Science and Electronics'', Thomson Learning, 1998 {{ISBN|1861527594}}</ref>\n\nmulti-turn trim potentiometers exist, in which it takes several turns of the adjustment screw to reach the end value. This allows for very high degrees of accuracy. Often they make use of a worm-gear (rotary track) or a leadscrew (linear track).<ref>{{cite web|title=Trimpot - Trimmer potentiometer|url=http://www.resistorguide.com/trimpot/|work=the Resistor Guide|accessdate=20 February 2013}}</ref> \n\n{|\n|-\n|[[File:Nedap ESD1 - Keyboard controller PCB - Bourns 3386-8588.jpg|upright=0.6|thumb|A top-adjust trimpot wtih sealing wax]]\n|[[File:Siemens RC 826 - trimmer pot-1728.jpg|upright=0.6|thumb|A side-adjust skeleton trimpot]]\n|[[File:10K trimpot.jpg|upright=0.5|thumb|A trimpot with knurling to allow finger adjustment]]\n|[[File:Bourns TRIMIT trimming potentiometer 2016-11-06.jpg|upright=0.8|thumb|A linear multi-turn trimpot]]\n|[[File:\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0446\u0438\u0437\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0435\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440.jpg|upright=0.6|thumb|A top-adjust circular-track multi-turn trimpot]]\n|}\n\n==Capacitors==\nTrimming capacitors can be multi-plate [[parallel-plate capacitor]]s with a dielectric for between plates for increased capacitance.  However, at [[SHF]] only very small values of capacitance are needed.  Presets at these frequencies are commonly a glass tube with plates at either end.  The top plate is adjusted by means of a screw to which it is attached at the top of the cylinder.\n\n==Inductors==\n* A common way of making preset inductors in radios is to wind the inductor on a plastic tube.  A high [[permeability]] core material is inserted into the cylinder in the form of a screw.  Winding the core further in to the inductor increases inductance and vice versa.  It is normally necessary to use non-metallic tools to adjust inductors.  A steel screwdriver will increase the inductance while it is being adjusted and it will fall again when the screwdriver is removed.\n\nAt VHF and SHF, only small values of inductance are usually needed.  Inductors can be made of open coils of a few turns.  They can be tuned by squeezing the coils together or by pulling them apart as the inductance needs to be increased or decreased respectively.\n\n==Tuned circuits==\n{{see also|Tuner (radio)}}\nAn adjustable tuned circuit can be formed in the same way as a preset inductor.  The inductor and its resonant capacitor are commonly contained in a metal can for shielding with a hole at the top to give access to the adjustable core.  Tuned transformers can also be constructed this way with two windings on the same core.  This is a common component in the [[intermediate frequency|IF stage]] of radios which have a [[double-tuned amplifier]] format.\n\n{|\n|-\n|[[File:IF transformer.JPG|thumb|upright=0.5|IF double-tuned transformer]]\n|[[File:Transformateur FI.jpg|thumb|upright|IF transformer can]]\n|[[File:IF transformer cutaway.jpg|thumb|upright=0.35|IF transformer cutaway]]\n|}\n\n==Distributed-element circuit==\n[[Distributed-element circuit]]s often use the component known as a [[Stub (electronics)|stub]].  In printed [[Planar transmission line|planar formats]] such as [[microstrip]], stubs can be trimmed by removing material with a scalpel or adding material by soldering on copper foil or even just pressing on strips of [[indium]].  This is useful for prototypes and pre-production runs, but is usually not done on production items.\n\n==Applications==\nThey are common in precision circuitry like [[Audiovisual|A/V]] components, and may need to be adjusted when the equipment is serviced. Trimpots are often used to initially calibrate equipment after manufacturing. Unlike many other variable controls, trimmers are mounted directly on [[circuit board]]s, turned with a small [[screwdriver]] and rated for many fewer adjustments over their lifetime. Trimmers like trimmable inductors and trimmable [[capacitor]]s are usually found in [[superhet]] [[radio]] and [[television]] receivers, in the [[intermediate frequency]] (IF), [[oscillator]] and radio frequency (RF) circuits. They are adjusted into the correct position during the alignment procedure.\n\n==Electronic symbols==\n[[Electronic symbol]]s for adjustable components.\n<gallery>\nFile:Potentiometer_symbol.svg|Electronic symbol for a resistive trimmer\nFile:Trimmer capacitor symbol GOST.svg|Electronic symbol for a capacitive trimmer\nFile:Reguleeritav pool.jpg|Electronic symbol for an adjustable inductor\n</gallery>\nn circuit diagrams, the symbol for a variable component is the symbol for a fixed component with a diagonal line through it terminating in an arrow head.  For a preset component, the diagonal line terminates in a \"T\" shape. \n\n==See also==\n* [[Laser trimming]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.robotroom.com/Trimpots.html Trimmer potentiometers (examples and internals)], Robot Room\n* [https://www.bourns.com/docs/technical-documents/technical-library/trimmers/technical-articles/trmrpmr.pdf Highlights from Trimmer Primers] - Bourns\n\n{{Electronic component}}\n\n[[Category:Resistive components]]\n[[Category:Capacitors]]\n\n[[de:Potentiometer#Trimmpotentiometer]]\n", "name_us